## 📈 Performance Results

| Dataset Size | Numbers | Time (4 cores) | Processing Speed |
|--------------|---------|----------------|------------------|
| 100 KB | 10,000 | 0.01 sec | 1,000,000 nums/sec |
| 100 MB | 14.6M | 27 sec | 540,000 nums/sec |
| **1 GB** | **145.4M** | **222 sec** | **654,000 nums/sec** |

### Performance Analysis
- **Linear scaling** with dataset size
- **Efficient load balancing** using MPI_Scatterv
- **Hash table performance** maintained via automatic rehashing (load factor 0.75)
- **4 processes** optimal for typical systems (matches physical cores)

---

## 🛠️ Technical Implementation

### 1. Dynamic Hash Table (Frequency Tracker)

```c
// Hash function with good distribution
unsigned int hash_function(large_int value, int capacity);

// Automatic rehashing when load factor > 0.75
if ((double)table->size / table->capacity > LOAD_FACTOR) {
    rehash(table);  // Doubles capacity
}
```

**Key Features:**
- **O(1)** average lookup and insertion
- **Sparse representation** - stores only unique values
- **Automatic resizing** to maintain performance
- **Chaining** for collision resolution

### 2. MPI Load Balancing

```c
// Distribute data unevenly when necessary
*local_size = total_size / size;
if (rank < total_size % size) {
    (*local_size)++;  // First k processes get one extra element
}

// Use MPI_Scatterv for non-uniform distribution
MPI_Scatterv(global_data, send_counts, displacements, MPI_INT64_T,
             *local_data, *local_size, MPI_INT64_T,
             0, MPI_COMM_WORLD);
```

### 3. Result Gathering

```c
// Reduce basic statistics
MPI_Reduce(&local_stats.min, &global_stats->min, 1, MPI_INT64_T, MPI_MIN, 0, ...);
MPI_Reduce(&local_stats.max, &global_stats->max, 1, MPI_INT64_T, MPI_MAX, 0, ...);
MPI_Reduce(&local_stats.sum, &global_stats->sum, 1, MPI_INT64_T, MPI_SUM, 0, ...);

// Manual merge for frequency tables
serialized_entry_t *entries = serialize_table(local_freq);
MPI_Send(entries, ...);
// Root process merges all tables using insert_with_count()
```

